===Etymology===
From [[Ancient Greek]] ''[[ξύλον]]'' + {{af|en|-itol|t1=anhydric alcohol}}.
===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}
# {{lb|en|chemistry}} A [[pentahydric]] [[alcohol]], C<sub>5</sub>H<sub>12</sub>O<sub>5</sub>, penta-hydroxy pentane; derived from [[xylose]]; used as a [[sweetener]].
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Matt Dorsey|title=Healthy Cocktails|year=2019|publisher=Simon and Schuster|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yXeNDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT29&dq=%22doggos%22&hl=&cd=63&source=gbs_api#v=onepage&q=%22doggos%22&f=false|isbn=978-1-5107-4495-0|author2=Jenny Dorsey|passage=A note of caution to readers with pets: '''Xylitol''' is toxic to dogs and can have potentially life-threatening effects. As owners of two doggos ourselves, we encourage anyone with a dog to use extreme caution when bringing '''xylitol''' into your home.}}
====Synonyms====
* {{l|en|E967}} when used as a sweetener
